text: Watched it yesterday, it's been a long time since I laughed and cried at the same time with a movie. The way it invigorates and reaffirms Spidey's cultural relevance  without abandoning its tone and sequential narrative is a work of deliberate art (the only one worth praising).  It gave me powerful Ninja Theory's DmC:  Devil May Cry vibes (the psychedelic palette, transitions between dimensions, the inverted falling scene, pretty obvious), along with anime film Paprika (a color explosion, almost literally). Truly amazing movie.   The only downside was, as usual, how Americans misinterpret anime style and conventions: (All good with a character like Peni Parker, but it really looks like a bad emulated anime style, and it shows A LOT as usual) They fail at character frames, proportions, eyes' size and expressions... and it seems they always will (Amerimanga SUCKS horribly), but Spider-Man's Noir conundrum with the Rubik Cube hypercompensated those shortcomings for me.  Great, great piece of work; let's hope nobody starts ripping off this style... I think Steve Ditko would've been proud.

text: My thoughts after seeing the movie are listed below:   Well, where do I start with this movie? Being an almost flawless origin story exploring Miles Morales struggles and his coming to terms with new founded super skills, it was set beautifully through the comic book animations. The film is the best film of 2018 and I really want to watch it a 5th time.    Well, I'm not really familiar with the comic books about Miles Morales, but I do consider myself an amateur Spider-Man fan, growing up watching Tobey Maguire defeat his opponents in the Sam Raimi trilogy. But this one was by far the best Spider-Man movie anyone could really ask for.     The humor is spectacularly displayed through the animation world of Spider-Verse, which to replicate in live action would be quite impossible. The input of thought bubbles was an amazing idea to see the progression and the thoughts from Miles. Seeing Miles Morales own clumsiness as he battles through what he calls puberty, and his old middle age Spider-Man mentor Peter B Parker's crusty experience and his self-doubt of being able to teach Morales adds to the humor. And adding onomatopoeia, including having bagel as onomatopoeia was also quite humorous.    This film well and truly explores the coming of age of a new Spider-Man who has more powers than the original. Focusing the spotlight on an Afro-Latino teenager, we are subjected to a soundtrack for the movie with a genre that is currently really popular even amongst young teenagers being hip-hop. The film doesn't fail to adequately describe how Miles Morales, a normal unexpecting teenager in the streets of Brooklyn, learns how to deal with superpowers that he had probably never wanted. But to really find himself, he goes through an emotional rollercoaster that triggers him finding himself.     My review would not be based much on the other characters but more on what this film was set to do; introduce Miles Morales. So in the film, for each different Spider-Men we see, we have a brief summary of their background, which allows for more character development. Except Miles' story is still being produced. The film's plot was almost flawless. The reason why I would say this is not because it was really much of a flaw, but something I would recommend on improving. Throughout the film, we can also see Miles' family problems, in being that Miles favors his uncle, Aaron Davis more than his own father, Jefferson Davis. We could see through the characters emotions that he has a special relationship with Aaron Davis, but the audience could not really sympathize with him much (well really me). SPOILER ALERT, when Aaron Davis was shot dead by Kingpin, we could see the hysteria caused by the non-diegetic sounds and the sadness dying in the arms of Miles. But personally, I couldn't really find that emotion. What I felt was that it was due to a lack of screen time for Aaron Davis. Its simple, we don't see him enough to miss him enough. A great example of this would be Wonder Woman. When Wonder Woman meets the pilot, she becomes acquainted with the pilot and the pilot shares a lot of screen time. When he dies at the end, both the audience and character feels the loss and empathize for the person dead. However, I felt that this was Spider Verse's most major flaw, and it is not even a flaw, just to show you how good this movie is.    What I did feel amazed by is how after the death and his failing to prove himself, he gets back up. Perhaps,  the thing that brought tears to my eyes was when Jefferson Davis gives Miles a mini-speech behind the door at the academy. The non-diegetic music adds to the sadness, and the father confessing to him about how much he pushed Miles because he sees a spark in him that is amazing really touches the heart. Obviously, this boost only sparks his powers, with which he finds out by taking a "leap of faith".     Being a spectacular Spider-Man film, which beautifully describes how a teenager finds himself, I would have to conclude by saying that Spider-Man: Into The Spider-Verse a solid movie.

text: SPOILER if you haven‚Äôt seen it yet.  A couple years ago if you were to ask me what I thought about Miles Morales Spiderman.  I probably would have told you he was crap and that another Spiderman that wasn‚Äôt Peter Park would be crap.  I actually decided to pick up one of Miles Morels comics, read it and to my surprise I actually really enjoyed it.     Went to Into the Spider Verse last night and I honestly really enjoyed it.  Probably the best Spiderman film to date. Real liked the story and the plot.  I may have gotten a little emotional when the original Spiderman died.  The female Doc Oc really surprised me which I thought was pretty cool.  Kingpin looked really weird and was huge but fun to watch.      Movie was really good .  Really good movie to take the kids to.  Highly recommend and I hope this is the start of something new.  Hope they decide to make some more.

text: This is one of the best animated movies ever created. Out of all films released in the Spider-Man franchise, this is my favorite. After watching the movie earlier today, I came home to watch the trailer.   From the animation style, screenplay, action, relationship between the characters, and everything in between, this movie was really entertaining.   I didn't think Sony had it in them, but the screenplay by Phil Lord and Rodney Rothman delivered. We cannot forget the great work from directors Peter Ramsay, Rodney Rothman, and Bob Persichetti. This isn't just a cool animated movie, but it's also an overall cool film. I am looking forward to the sequel.

There's dumb and there's Marvel comics human dumb.   I mean let's say you do arrest or shoot him. What happens next time when Green Goblin or some other crazy villain is destroying the city and you police can't do squat? Who'll save you all then idiots? text: Guys, don't judge a movie based on what the directors opinions are on politics and social justice. Everything in this trailer shows clear accuracy to the comics. Miles Morales is a boy that also got bitten by the same spider and has to succeed Peter Parker, becoming his own Spider-Man. Gwen Stacy, while not in the same universe (although it's called "Into the Spider-Verse" for a reason) also became a Spider-Woman. If an agenda doesn't get shoved down my throat, I'm fine with this movie. I mean, he's gonna be in a costume so it's not like the public will judge the new Spider-Man for being black, just a new kid. They might make the public judge the suit, it being black instead, but we can see that Peter already has had that suit in his collection.

text: You can like art and not agree with the people who made it. I dont agree with the director's opinions and statements he's made on Twitter, but you have to realize he wasn't the only one who made the movie. The voice actors, animators, the studio, the musicians, they also helped bring this to life. They deserve their recognition for the hard work they've done instead of their work being ignored because of the person who's running the project. If the director makes a mistake the entire team shouldn't have to suffer too. That's like if the quarterback of your favorite NFL team said something horrible, the rest of the team shouldn't have to suffer because of someone else's actions. If you still dont want to see the movie, that's fine it's your choice. But dont let the actions of one person on a team make or break your opinion of a movie.

text: It seems that Into the Spider-Verse will be introducing viewers to Miles Morales (voiced by Shameik Moore) as he grows into his role as Spider-Man, mentored by an older, more inveterate take on Peter Parker (voiced by Jake Johnson) than any we‚Äôve seen before.  Not only will Miles Morales ‚Äî the Afro-Latinx teen who became the first non-white iteration of the swinging superhero with Marvel‚Äôs Ultimate line of comics in 2011 ‚Äî be taking to the streets of New York in Into the Spider-Verse, but there‚Äôs also a glimpse of Spider-Gwen. She‚Äôs another popular take on the character in yet another universe where Gwen Stacy gets the radioactive spider-powers instead.    I‚Äôd be remiss in not pointing out that the art style of the film is absolutely gorgeous, with a textured, brightly colored vibe that looks like someone blended a comic book with Pixar-style 3D animation.   The new trailer also gives a bit more context about the setting of Into the Spider-Verse for fans who might not be as well-versed in the universe-hopping shenanigans of comic books. According to Morales‚Äô voiceover, the film takes place in ‚Äúanother universe, that looks and sounds like yours ‚Äî but it‚Äôs not.‚Äù (So don‚Äôt expect to see Tom Holland‚Äôs incarnation of the character swinging through the streets.)  "Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse" new trailer was released alongside  "Incredibles 2" In U.K. & Ireland Cinema Locations "Ant Man and the Wasp" "Hotel Transylvania 3: Summer Vacation" "Mission: Impossible - Fallout" In AMC Theaters Locations "Christopher Robin" "Alpha" "A-X-L" & "The House With a Clock in its Walls  If you saw this trailer read the Replies below

text: This Movie will be A Surprise Hit Superhero Movie of 2018 A Family Friendly action packed superhero film about the most popular superhero of all time; the Marvel Character created By Stan Lee: Spider-Man. The highly stylized amazing vibrant and colorful eye popping art and visuals paired with brand new innovative motion picture film animation and computer generation graphics which has not been used yet is a groundbreaking style in visual storytelling inspired by and meant to honor the original source material: The Comics Created by Stan Lee, Steve Ditko, Avi Arad, and The Creators of the many other Spider-Man characters in the Marvel Comics Universe We all Know & Love. This movie is groundbreaking not only because it features a mostly predominantly Black African American Cast as well as The Main Character as Spider-Man Created By Donald Glover. It will also be the First Animated Movie Ever To Be Rated PG-13

text: The dad is maybe the best character I have seen in years. Love every single thing about him.  Miles looks great too. Maybe even better then the original.  Peter.. I don't really like this version so far, but the 90s Peter Parker beeing my alltime favorit hero of all time makes me obviously bias. As a mentor he might be pretty interesting.  Gwen could be great. I liked the Spider-Gwen character in the comics so there is potential.  The villans so far look stupid. I never liked the Ultimate Green Goblin monster and the Kingpin (if this even is him) is a little much too. Especially because it looks like his size doesn't even matter when he is thrown around just like anybody else is.. The kid in the cape.. don't recognise him. He looks cool so I'm optimistic.  Music, artstyle, animation.... everything looks really good.  conclusion: I am hyped and I hope Sony will do more awesome stuff like this with the license instead of chasing the big movie crowd. Just as DCs animated movies are awesome and deserve more recognition while their movies are just bad..

text: Okay so here's my own personal theory with whats going on here especially with the two different Spiderman voices: The Peter we see in the diner with the burger looks much older than most incarnations, rather looking in his 20s he has graying hair it could be in his 40s+. We also see later on at the Gwen Stacy segment that he doesn't apparently have a full costume and neither does miles. Yet later we see Miles explaining the multiverse with "Two Spidermen" to who we assume is another Peter.  So I think whats going to happen is that there are 2 universes that will be delved upon (probably a LOT more with this Gwen Stacy reveal), Old Parker (with Miles) and Young Parker (no miles). In the old Parker universe he is near the end of his career, he has all the suits from the comics and the public knows who he is. Miles gets bitten and goes through his origin, EXCEPT Peter takes him on as a sidekick or protege. However in some sort of fight (possibly ending with miles being sent through to the Young Parker universe) Old Parker will die (thus the Peter Parker grave stone in the first trailer). Beforehand I think Old Parker may introduce Miles to the idea of a Multiverse (assuming that this Parker is a future 'Version' of the 616 one and has done interdimensional stuff before). For whatever reason, Miles will be sent to a universe where there is still a inexperienced spiderman. The one who asks "How is this possible".  Alternatively this could be the the other way around, Miles lives in the young Parker universe as a rookie but is sent to old Parker universe and learns.   Probably wrong but that's my take on things.

text: This movie looks absolutely marvelous! I adore the art style! It almost looks like a painting in motion that came to life, which gives it a 3D yet mostly 2D look. I also love how fluid the animation is. Disney's Tangled was supposed to have a look like this originally when it was still called "Rapunzel Unbraided", to make it look like a painting in motion, but they went for the generic CGI look instead. I would never expect for a Spiderman movie to go with this look, but I'm impressed that they did! I would love to see this movie!

text: *Hey you!*          Hi, I'm TakeTheJurny, just a fellow small Youtuber with a big dream >_< I can't explain how much this means to me that you are giving me your time just to read this comment, and I know you probably are ready to go see a different video or maybe just look at your phone but, it really does mean a lot, because in our society time is very precious. So thanks for reading. Now that I've got your full attention. *M-MHM* I have worked very hard on my Youtube but I fear that the new rules and regulations and the terrible "adpocalypse" are going to be hard to surpass by taking the classic "Make a viral video" seems. So I have decided to comment here, on a viral video, and yes some may say this is advertising, and perhaps it is but please, hear me out. Right now there are 31,139 comments on this video. If every single person that commented on this video saw this comment and took a look at my channel and subscribed literally my dreams would come TRUE!!!! I mean, think about that for a second, we all, working together could make MY DREAMS COME TRUE! and I'm not even asking everyone to subscribe because I only want people who truly enjoy my work to sub, and I'm perfectly fine with that! I'm just trying to find the fastest and easiest way to give everyone a chance to see my work and enjoy it, as well as better my chances for growing as a Youtuber! Now let me rephrase my dream, just so you truly understand my goal...(also thanks so much for still reading!).   *FLASHBACK NARRATION SCENE OF ME AS A LITTLE KID*  I had a rough childhood. My father hurt me and my mom for 13 crappy years, crazy right? It finally shook my mom and she left, but I loved my dad still so much I stayed even though it totally sucked because he'd constantly hurt me, and I don't want to get too detailed because, well, kids might be reading-- anyways, that plus I was always outcasted from my classmates in school and I was pretty much stuck watching Netflix and eating to have fun at the time. It was always hard for me to see the bright side of things and I was losing hope as I sunk deep in to a sort of young depression. That is until I found something.. So I had never really watched Youtube at the time and I thought it was kind of boring tbh. But I was crying that day and looking for enjoyment. Then it was on the screen. "Markiplier's Let's Play Slender The Arrival!" I was so excited because I LOVED Slenderman so much, so with that in mind I clicked, not knowing what was to happen...but what would happen, would change my life forever. (Hey just another thumbs up for still reading!! I know it's a lot sorry!!).   As I watched Markiplier, as I listened to his positive glow and saw his bright booming smile as he squealed at different things about the game. I noticed something starting to change. I had stopped crying. I was also now smiling, focused and laughing at the video! Ever since then I kept watching his videos WHENEVER I was down, or sad or unhappy. His videos never failed to lift me up and cleanse me of my darkness. As he wandered down dark corners bravely, I wandered with him. Like a family. I wanted to share this feeling of happiness. This feeling of peace even in chaos! I wanted anyone like me to see this so that they would be happy too, so that we could all be positive and for once have some sort of universal truth of peace and a wonderful family. I want to do what he does. I want to make YOU smile when no one else is. YOU laugh on a bad day. and YOU can be my family when yours isn't there for you. (SORRY I'LL HURRY THIS UP! Dang you still reading? wow!)   So, my dream is to be what Markiplier was to me. A light in a person's darkness. I just want to make everyone laugh and bring everyone together. So that's why I made my Youtube. TakeTheJurny, because life is a Journey. Now I just want to say that this is not spam, this is a choice. No one has to sub I just wanted everyone to have a chance to see my Youtube before it hits 1million, and that will happen one day :) thanks for reading, and as always I will see you, when I heed the call, to the next Journey, Adios guys! <3 and thanks so much for reading!

But I even watched the first Maguire movie back in 2001 on cinema (it ended up to be the whole trilogy, just like with LotR). Back then I felt the same thing I felt now watching this trailer. It was refreshing, and nostalgic. Hope it‚Äôs good.

text: So this is my analysis/theory: Miles is just your ordinary kid blah blah blah, maybe he's interested in Spider-Man but his dad definitely isn't. But he somehow gets bit by the radioactive spider, and one day he gets caught in the middle of a fight between Spider-Man and the Green Goblin and Spider-Man rescues him and finds out Miles is the same as him. So Miles is being tutored by Peter and maybe one by one more Spider Dudes show up? But there was that one clip where Peter is fighting a purple Spider guy (maybe) but then in one clip when they're training they meet Spider-Gwen. Also Peter seems to where his suit in public so maybe people know his identity. I saw Kingpin in there too. So maybe with the more Spider Guys showing up there might dimensional traveling or alternate villains show up too. I kinda hope I'm wrong so I'm more surprised bit also some details are true. Miles has a weaker spidey sense than peters but a couple extra abilites such as invisibility and a paralyzing blast he calls "venom shock". text: [Black] People are getting excited about Spider-Man being black. As a black person who's very  "aware"  of certain things I'm not going to get my hopes up yet. Why? Well, because even though everyone knows that Spider-Man is a superhero - in this case (unlike previous movies) he's not really going to be the sole star/hero of the show. He'd be sharing the spotlight with experts in the field of "Superheroism" and whilst the initial impression is, hey black people we gave you a superhero - they (the experts) will be the true stars / heroes and (positive) center of attention. My concern - since proven right in the past - is that  he will portrayed as the typical black person who: is naive (novice) / has self-doubt / is academically-challenged / has is siting on his gifts and talents and, therefore, needs to be mentored by a non-black person that will be responsible for educating / refining / gentrifying / uplifting / empowering .. him because - of course - he (the black person) would not be able to accomplish those things on his own or from other members of his (black) community.  Based on the trailer... there seems to be a somewhat subliminal black-on-black opposition  and crab-in-the-bucket thing going n when the (black) father is the one who's against (black) Spider-Man (his son). My concern is that people's subconscious would be triggered to think that he's another annoying black man trying to hold back progress for the good of the people.    ...and, yes, the conspiracy theorist in me is not wondering if someone is pushing more black superheros because their aware that more black folks will be willing to spend their "liquid" finances on cosplay and Halloween costumes.  That's not to say that I'm fighting anyone's hustle... I just want to be sure that black people are not exploited, mocked and taken for fools in the process. That said - though I'm no expert I have a great appreciation for animated shows - and great appreciation I mean LOVE... I no longer have the love I used for T.V shows and movies because of the very same issues mentioned above (and then some) but this movies has a lot of potential.

text: This movie might actually be good. Let me explain.   Miles Morales, probably one of the most one dimensional characters in Marvel Comics (mainly because he is basically just Peter Parker) is now getting a movie where he can finally distinct himself from Peter. Michael Bendis, the man who created the character Miles Morales was afraid to let Miles do anything on his own. Bendis made Miles always say (not always but sometimes) ‚ÄúGee, I wonder what Peter would do‚Äù or something like that. This movie might ignore that and instead ask ‚ÄúWhat would Miles Do‚Äù or something. If this is answered, the movie might finally make Miles Morales a better character and make him be better written better than the person who made him. That would be awesome.   I can‚Äôt wait for this movie.

text: At first I didn't care for the art style when I saw the first trailer, but I'm really liking it now.  Everything looks and seems great, except two things:  1. I don't like how they're portraying Peter Parker, I don't know what it is exactly, but something just feels off to me, I don't know if it's the voice actor, or the way he's teaching Miles, or what, but something is off.  2. I don't like them shoehorning in Spider-Gwen, this should've just been Miles's movie, the chance to bring him to a wider audience and have them get to know his character better and maybe even make him a better character in terms of not always being a copycat Peter Parker, now it seems (like classic Sony) they're trying to squeeze too much into one movie.  I hope these two points are dead wrong and it will turn out that Peter is the Peter we know and love and the inclusion of Spider-Gwen is natural and actually necessary to the plot of the movie, but given Sony's track record, and the fact that they needed Marvel's help to make good Spider-Man movies again...  Needless to say, I have my doubts.

text: 1: I love the animation style, it literally looks like a comic book coming to life on screen 2: I don't love his voice, but Peter is spot on. He's broke enough to ask a kid to pay the bill. He understands and relays to Miles that the goal is to just protect innocent people, not save the entire world, just be the "friendly neighborhood Spider-Man". And in the end, he's wearing cargo pants, meaning he still loses pieces of his costume that he has to remake. 3: So glad Miles is finally on the big screen, and they nailed his character. He's a kid who gets embarrassed by his parents, but is sassy enough to still be confident as Spidey and question Peter's teaching methods. 4: Gwen Stacy isn't going to be just the girlfriend or smart nerdy girl, which is a major jump from her last cinematic appearance. Now we don't have to deal with the "fridging" problem. 5: I hope they really pull off the villains well, because it seems like there's gonna be a lot of them. The creature Peter was fighting is most likely Goblin or Lizard, not sure who the black suit guy was (Prowler, maybe), and I believe I saw the shadow of Kingpin in that explosion scene. 6: 1:57, we've all been there, Miles.

text: For the new generation of spider man lovers or if youre not caught up, this movie is based on obviously spider man, but from a different universe hence spider-verse. You see, each different spiderman you see is from a different universe in itself. So this spiderman isnt the same one from Infinity war, homecoming, or even the first three spiderman movies. In this universe, it's a little bit based off of the first spiderman movie, where peter is bit by a spider and gains these powers protecting new york. The main character, Miles Morales, also gets bit by a spider similar to Peter's. Later in the story, as seen from the first trailer, Peter dies. In the comic, he dies from the green goblin, but who knows what'll happen in this one? So, its Miles' turn now to take on the role of being the spiderman  Pls correct me if im wrong on any of these or if i forgot anything, thank you

text: Wow! This hurt to watch. I appreciate that they're going for a comic book look, but it's like they found some Ben-Day and halftone pattern plug-ins online and just slapped them on top of their existing animation and called it a day. Seriously, there are shots in here that look like they're supposed to be 3D and I'm not wearing the glasses. Some are just ridiculously blurry. No, not blurry. More just the same imagery on top of itself multiple times and then shifted slightly. What is actually good animation is buried under this garbage.  There there's whoever is voicing Peter. Jake Johnson according to Google? Sorry, but he sounds so flat and awful. You guys know this is an animated film right? I'm so fucking tired of hearing on camera actors, who can seemingly only act if they're on set, stumble awkwardly through a voice over role. Seriously, you couldn't have gotten Dan Gilvezan or Christopher Daniel Barnes or heck how about Neil Patrick Harris? You know, somebody who is older and has played Spider-Man before. Which is clearly what this version of him is supposed to be.  I'm also confused where this film is going. From the first teaser and the title, I thought this was going to be about the comic book event. But I guess they're just using the term "Spider-verse" because you got Peter, Miles, and Gwen in the same universe. But then why not just call it Ultimate Spider-Man? And what about the line about how "in your universe there's only one Spider-Man..."? So is there going to be some universe hopping or not?

text: Okay so I see they're keeping and mashing things. Originally Peter Parker was admired and hated (Ultimate comics run). Well known. Then when he died everyone was devastated. Miles had gained his powers right before Peter died and he was even there to witness Peter's death. He then was on his own and tried his hardest to become the next spider man. He had a good solo. THEN SPIDER VERSE HAPPENED. Peter was more of a Jedi ghost to Miles, Through newspapers and internet pictures, not right there with him at the start of his career. Later in his life he DID meet Peter even before SPIDER-VERSE. It was a run where Miles even fought alongside Peter against the monster that killed Peter in the first place (Green Goblin). It's not annoying but weird to me that they couldn't kill off Peter for this movie. Maybe this is another universe's Peter but still.
